summaries.title: Recognizing Privilege and Peer Disparities in Engineering Education
summaries.summaryText: Ethan discussed observing classmates who struggled to access tutoring or networking opportunities. His reflection on his own privilege as a continuing-generation student led him to advocate for more peer tutoring support and accessible design lab hours. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Balancing Academic Rigor with Limited Peer Representation
summaries.summaryText: Maria described feeling academically capable but often isolated in her computer engineering courses, where few other Latina students were enrolled. She mentioned that faculty were supportive when approached, but that representation and group belonging remained low, especially during first-year lab sections. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Building Inclusive Engineering Teams
summaries.summaryText: Ethan noted that successful project outcomes often came from teams with diverse backgrounds and perspectives. He believes empathy and active listening should be core engineering competencies. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: First-Generation Challenges in Navigating University Systems
summaries.summaryText: Maria described difficulty understanding financial aid processes and navigating academic advising resources. She relied heavily on peer networks and informal guidance, noting that the institutional language often assumed prior family familiarity with college systems. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Balancing Pressure, Pride, and Belonging
summaries.summaryText: Daniel expressed pride in representing his family’s aspirations but also noted ongoing struggles with imposter syndrome. He values belonging through peer groups that normalize his experiences as a first-gen student of color in STEM. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Microaggressions and Invisible Labor in Group Dynamics
summaries.summaryText: Aaliyah recounted repeated experiences of having her technical input questioned in group settings. She also described taking on emotional labor to support other students facing similar bias. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Developing Leadership Confidence Through Robotics Projects
summaries.summaryText: Ethan described how leading design sprints in the robotics club refined his communication and teamwork skills. He recognized his relative advantage from prior exposure to engineering through his family, and expressed an interest in mentoring peers with less background experience. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Family Support and Pressure as a Dual Motivation
summaries.summaryText: As a first-generation student, Daniel’s parents provided emotional encouragement but limited academic guidance. Their sacrifices motivated him, though he expressed anxiety about failing to meet expectations. [Part 3/4]

themes.title: Emotional Labor and Advocacy Burden in Underrepresented Students
themes.description: Aaliyah’s experience illustrates how women of color in engineering often balance advocacy roles with academic demands, leading to invisible emotional labor that institutions rarely acknowledge. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Peer Mentorship as a Belonging Intervention
themes.description: Daniel emphasized how structured mentorship programs provided psychological safety and belonging cues, normalizing struggle and improving persistence among marginalized students. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Acknowledging Structural Advantage and Allyship in STEM
themes.description: Ethan’s reflections underscore the role of allyship among students who recognize their positional privilege. He highlights how acknowledging systemic inequities can lead to more equitable classroom dynamics. [Extended 2]

themes.title: Sense of Belonging in STEM for Students of Color
themes.description: Maria’s reflections highlight how peer representation and visibility in classrooms significantly influence belonging and persistence for Latina women in engineering. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Mentorship Networks as Retention Mechanisms
themes.description: Mentorship emerges as a consistent strategy for increasing belonging and persistence for students from marginalized groups. Aaliyah’s mentorship program demonstrates how peer-led initiatives can fill institutional gaps. [Extended 2]

themes.title: Acknowledging Structural Advantage and Allyship in STEM
themes.description: Ethan’s reflections underscore the role of allyship among students who recognize their positional privilege. He highlights how acknowledging systemic inequities can lead to more equitable classroom dynamics. [Extended 4]

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Peer Mentoring for First-Generation STEM Students
areasForImprovement.description: Formalize mentoring programs that pair upperclassmen with first-generation students early in their academic journey. These networks reduce imposter syndrome and improve retention rates. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Create opt-in mentoring tracks for first-gen students
Provide mentor training focused on inclusive communication

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Visibility of First-Gen Student Resources
areasForImprovement.description: Current communication about financial aid, academic advising, and mentorship resources does not adequately reach first-generation students. Improving targeted outreach through orientation and department emails could reduce inequities in access to support. [Extended 3]
actionItems: Add first-gen resource links to department portals
